And my second question.

97
00:06:22,904 --> 00:06:24,197
Park Gi-ppeum.

98
00:06:24,280 --> 00:06:25,489
Yes, Professor?

99
00:06:25,573 --> 00:06:28,034
-You did great on the interview.
-Thank you, sir.

100
00:06:28,117 --> 00:06:30,786
Now that the interview is over,
let's talk freely.

101
00:06:31,495 --> 00:06:32,997
Why do you want to practice law?

102
00:06:33,080 --> 00:06:34,916
This is an industry in decline now.

103
00:06:34,999 --> 00:06:38,419
As I said earlier,
I want to protect basic human rights

104
00:06:38,502 --> 00:06:41,214
-and social justice--
-Come on. The interview's over.

105
00:06:41,297 --> 00:06:43,007
Not that stuff. The real reason.

106
00:06:44,634 --> 00:06:48,429
-That's the real reason.
-Okay, then.

107
00:06:48,512 --> 00:06:51,015
But being a nerd and reality
were two different things.

108
00:06:51,515 --> 00:06:53,309
After that,
nothing had made my heart pound

109
00:06:53,935 --> 00:06:55,645
for a very long time.

110
00:06:56,771 --> 00:06:59,065
-But…
-This poor abandoned dog

111
00:06:59,148 --> 00:07:01,192
was brutally abused and thrown out.

112
00:07:02,276 --> 00:07:05,988
Is she really the dog you lost?

113
00:07:06,072 --> 00:07:08,032
No! No, it's not mine.

114
00:07:08,783 --> 00:07:10,534
My heart raced in that moment…

115
00:07:11,535 --> 00:07:12,536
for a split second.

116
00:07:15,164 --> 00:07:16,123
Geez.

117
00:07:16,666 --> 00:07:18,000
Forget about it,

118
00:07:18,543 --> 00:07:19,710
and just trust me.

119
00:07:19,794 --> 00:07:22,213
I mean, what's there to worry about?

120
00:07:22,296 --> 00:07:24,298
Kang Da-wit, the people's judge, is here.

121
00:07:24,382 --> 00:07:27,510
Of course, your skills are incredible.

122
00:07:27,593 --> 00:07:30,179
-I admire you. I really do.
-Then, what's the problem?

123
00:07:30,263 --> 00:07:33,975
Doing this international patent case
worth trillions

124
00:07:35,268 --> 00:07:37,937
that's between conglomerates
doesn't seem right.

125
00:07:38,020 --> 00:07:40,982
We're a pro bono team, after all.

126
00:07:41,065 --> 00:07:43,818
Geez. This is so frustrating.

127
00:07:45,361 --> 00:07:46,654
What's public interest?

128
00:07:47,738 --> 00:07:49,240
We're one team now,

129
00:07:49,323 --> 00:07:51,993
so let's speak honestly.

130
00:07:52,076 --> 00:07:54,370
If we win and make a lot of money,

131
00:07:54,453 --> 00:07:56,622
where does that money go?

132
00:07:56,706 --> 00:08:00,626
The money circulates, so the common folk
and disadvantaged will benefit from it.

133
00:08:01,335 --> 00:08:04,922
Making money is
the most pro bono thing we can do.

134
00:08:05,590 --> 00:08:06,882
Day and night, we do these.

135
00:08:06,966 --> 00:08:09,594
These cases don't even make money.

136
00:08:09,677 --> 00:08:11,220
We expend energy for nothing.

137
00:08:11,304 --> 00:08:13,514
Why on earth do we do these?

138
00:08:13,598 --> 00:08:15,224
What's this? A refugee case?

139
00:08:15,308 --> 00:08:17,935
Young people are livid
that they can't find jobs these days.

140
00:08:18,019 --> 00:08:20,980
Who'd be happy
about foreigners coming in?

141
00:08:21,063 --> 00:08:24,525
What else? Human rights for people
with disabilities? It sounds wonderful.

142
00:08:24,609 --> 00:08:26,819
Right? But whenever people
with disabilities protest,

143
00:08:26,902 --> 00:08:29,822
do you know how angry people get
when they can't properly commute?

144
00:08:30,448 --> 00:08:33,409
God, instead of stuff like this,

145
00:08:33,492 --> 00:08:34,952
let's do something classy--

146
00:08:35,036 --> 00:08:38,080
I can't listen to this anymore!

147
00:08:38,664 --> 00:08:43,628
Do I have to keep listening to him deny
the very existence of pro bono cases?

148
00:08:43,711 --> 00:08:45,004
What? You have nothing to say?

149
00:08:45,588 --> 00:08:47,506
Am I the only one who's uncomfortable?

150
00:08:48,341 --> 00:08:49,508
Come on, Ms. Yoo.

151
00:08:49,592 --> 00:08:52,094
Why does everything
make you so uncomfortable?

152
00:08:52,178 --> 00:08:55,014
If you're uncomfortable,
go and sit somewhere comfortable.

153
00:09:00,603 --> 00:09:02,188
You stupid boomer!

154
00:09:03,856 --> 00:09:04,690
What?

155
00:09:05,274 --> 00:09:06,108
"Stupid boomer"?

156
00:09:06,859 --> 00:09:07,902
Unbelievable.

157
00:09:07,985 --> 00:09:09,111
What? "Boomer"?

158
00:09:09,654 --> 00:09:11,113
I've never been called that before.

159
00:09:11,197 --> 00:09:13,574
Hey, Ms. Yoo. What did you say? "Boomer"?

160
00:09:13,658 --> 00:09:14,492
What?

161
00:09:14,575 --> 00:09:17,912
Back in my day, you wouldn't dare
speak that way to senior colleagues!

162
00:09:17,995 --> 00:09:20,373
-My heart of a nerd…
-"Boomer?" Man, things have changed.

163
00:09:20,456 --> 00:09:22,249
It must have been a false alarm.

164
00:09:22,792 --> 00:09:24,877
No wonder they say
face reading was a science.

165
00:09:25,461 --> 00:09:27,505
He didn't seem right from the start.

166
00:09:27,588 --> 00:09:28,839
Excuse me, Mr. Kang.

167
00:09:28,923 --> 00:09:30,883
Which graduating class
are you from, Ms. Yoo?

168
00:09:30,966 --> 00:09:32,635
-Mr. Kang.
-Ms. Yoo--

169
00:09:36,555 --> 00:09:37,807
What now, Ms. Park?

170
00:09:37,890 --> 00:09:40,851
Why did you come to Team Pro Bono?

171
00:09:45,314 --> 00:09:46,524
Why are you suddenly asking?

172
00:09:47,274 --> 00:09:49,193
You said it yourself.

173
00:09:49,735 --> 00:09:52,113
You used to handle only the classy cases.

174
00:09:52,988 --> 00:09:55,533
Why did you quit being a judge

175
00:09:55,616 --> 00:09:56,992
and come here?

176
00:09:58,786 --> 00:10:00,246
Did you know, Mr. Kang?

177
00:10:00,329 --> 00:10:03,416
If there are people in this world
who always win,

178
00:10:03,499 --> 00:10:06,377
there are people who always lose as well.

179
00:10:06,460 --> 00:10:10,047
No matter how hard they try,
they're too weak to fight the world.

180
00:10:10,131 --> 00:10:13,008
Pro bono attorneys exist
to help people like them,

181
00:10:14,093 --> 00:10:17,680
not to handle classy cases
or cases they always win.

182
00:10:22,601 --> 00:10:24,145
Why do you think I wouldn't know

183
00:10:25,479 --> 00:10:27,273
about the ones who always lose?

184
00:10:28,107 --> 00:10:31,152
The ones too weak to fight the world,
no matter how hard they try.

185
00:10:33,320 --> 00:10:34,321
You think I don't know?

186
00:10:39,660 --> 00:10:42,371
But do you know what it's like, Ms. Park?

187
00:10:42,455 --> 00:10:44,957
Have you even tried
to earn your own tuition yourself?

188
00:10:45,499 --> 00:10:47,418
You're crossing the line, Mr. Kang.

189
00:10:47,501 --> 00:10:49,545
Right. This is an uncomfortable question.

190
00:10:49,628 --> 00:10:52,006
You must've been offended.
Sorry. Excuse me.

191
00:10:52,089 --> 00:10:54,884
No. Thanks to my parents,

192
00:10:54,967 --> 00:10:57,386
I grew up comfortably
and was raised by a loving family.

193
00:10:57,470 --> 00:10:58,554
Yes, I can surely tell.

194
00:10:58,637 --> 00:11:00,347
And what about it?

195
00:11:01,223 --> 00:11:02,183
Is that a problem?

196
00:11:02,266 --> 00:11:03,267
No, who says it is?

197
00:11:03,350 --> 00:11:06,061
That's great. Gosh, how amazing.

198
00:11:06,145 --> 00:11:09,440
Someone raised with love
is worrying about the people in need.

199
00:11:09,523 --> 00:11:11,901
How honorable.
Any thoughts of becoming a politician?

200
00:11:11,984 --> 00:11:14,028
I'll help you.
I have a lot of connections.

201
00:11:15,279 --> 00:11:16,280
Oh, my gosh!

202
00:11:17,072 --> 00:11:17,907
Ms. Park.

203
00:11:23,078 --> 00:11:24,288
2025 SEOUL QUEER FESTIVAL

204
00:11:27,917 --> 00:11:30,336
Follow me.
You have to come to see me, sister.

205
00:11:31,629 --> 00:11:33,005
I wish we could get married.

206
00:11:33,088 --> 00:11:37,259
We're just a tiny bit different.
That's all.

207
00:11:37,343 --> 00:11:39,053
Please try to understand.

208
00:11:39,637 --> 00:11:41,138
We'll walk you down the aisle!

209
00:11:41,222 --> 00:11:42,306
We're with you.

210
00:11:42,389 --> 00:11:43,891
Please give us a hug!

211
